Did you recruit talent for the company?
That's how you'll keep your competitors from "hijacking" it from you.
The economy is still in a labor market that is largely controlled by the workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents •
Here are some tips to help you maintain it in the workplace
.
Despite the increase registered in the last month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be one of the lowest in the world, and in the top ten among the OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the CBS).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is mostly controlled by the workers and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents.
As far as those professionals and managers who are centers of proven knowledge, experience and ability are concerned - the trends in the labor market show that the competition for them, the talents as they are called by the employers, still exists in full force.
The meaning of this for employers is that in the current state of the labor market, they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after the recruitment of a desirable talent, because as soon as he enters the company's gates - another company will already try to kidnap him.
In other words, the competition for talent is so intense that many, even after being hired, will continue to receive a host of tempting job offers, when 30% of employees actually leave only a month after accepting the position and starting work.
This is the reason why wise employers will immediately move from the phase of recruiting talent to the phase of retaining it, when the path begins first and foremost with preparation in advance and taking creativity already in the process of absorbing it.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful absorption process will make the talent enthusiastic about his new workplace from the very first day and even look forward to the future.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a correct absorption process that will help in retaining the new talent:
It's not a secret - sharing and organization readiness
Share the factors that will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is essential and important to the company and the position, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where he is expected and understands his value, will feel welcome and strive to prove the expectations placed on him.
Knowledge is power - coordination of expectations
Already on the first day, have a meeting with the talent to coordinate expectations.
Get to know his professional background and check where he sees himself in the future, so that you can show him the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people - personal acquaintance
During the days of absorption, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and take an interest in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who shows interest in him and allows him to realize and express himself beyond the limits of his role will appreciate it and want to keep it that way.
Curiosity promotes
Already in the absorption phase you can create an attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily by talking about bonuses and benefits, but by exposing him to an exciting field or an interesting technology, since this type of stimulation for creativity leads to increased curiosity and interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the talent to voice their thoughts and opinions on the various projects in the company and make it clear to them that they are important to the organization.
The author is the CEO of Manpower Israel - the largest placement and manpower company in Israel
Electrification in your pocket: the cost of not closing the coal stations in June - one billion shekels
Report of the Knesset's Research and Information Center: The failure to close the coal plants on the date set in June 2022 is estimated at about one billion shekels
• The Electric Company: "The fuel usage policy is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy"
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal plants by the date set in June 2022 is estimated at about one billion shekels for the year 2022, according to a report by the Knesset's Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is embodied in the electricity tariff for the consumer, which, as mentioned, is expected to increase in the coming months due to the increase in the price of coal.
In addition to this, in 2023 an additional excess amount of coal use of approximately 900 thousand tons is expected, so that this will be reflected in an additional cost to the electricity sector for not closing the coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report states that the reduction of approximately one billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 meant a reduction of approximately 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for the home consumer.
That is, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about a billion shekels, and the total discount that could have been for the home consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform in the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the Electric Company, which will build units powered by natural gas, intended to replace the coal-fired units 4-1 at the Orot Rabin site.
Further to this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, stating that the activity of the coal-fired production units 4-1 at the Orot Rabin power plant must be stopped.
The decision established timetables, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly the coal-fired production units 4-1 will also stop operating at that time.
The electricity company responded: "The fuel usage policy is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry's decisions, a policy of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible has been implemented in Israel for several years, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas."
Paying the price: everything you need to know ahead of the interest rate hike
Constant decrees: next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to increase by half a percent •
How much more expensive will the mortgage payment be?
And what is recommended to do? •
all the answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
The analysts' estimates speak of an increase rate ranging from 0.25% to 0.5%.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percent, it will already stand at 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This, after for years the interest rate in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate increases the mortgage repayments by hundreds of shekels and drastically burdens the households.
With the help of Shai Zror, a mortgage expert, we checked how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate increases by half a percent - how much more expensive will the monthly payment on the mortgage be?
For a mortgage in the amount of NIS 1.2 million, which consists of a 40% prime interest track, the monthly repayment will increase by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage become more expensive since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this is a significantly sharper increase.
This is because the interest rates on the other tracks that make up a mortgage (and not just the prime track) have also gone up - in the index-linked track and the fixed interest track.
If the interest rate does go up by half a percent, the increase in price will amount, according to Zror's estimate, to about NIS 620 on a mortgage of about NIS 1.2 million.
The prime route (40% in this route) will complete a price increase of about NIS 280, assuming there will be another 0.5% increase next month.
The index-linked variable interest rate (26.7% on this rate) will add up to a price increase of about NIS 120.
The fixed interest track - not linked to an index (33.3% in this track) will become more expensive by NIS 220.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have an index-linked rifle mortgage, Saror recommends considering recycling to routes that are not index-linked.
For mortgage holders whose monthly repayments have increased significantly and it is difficult for them to meet the repayments - he recommends looking into recycling a mortgage and redeploying it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite the increase in interest rates, since it is always better to meet the repayments and not be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage takers - he strongly recommends getting to know the different routes and adapting the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
So also in the future when the interest rates will drop, they will be able to recycle a mortgage with minimal early repayment fees.
Regarding apartment buyers from a contractor - Seror recommends making payments to the contractor in advance and taking out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction input index" raises the price of the property significantly even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The price index of residential construction inputs increased by 6.6% in the last year.
Against the background of the increase in the price of this index, on Tuesday the supervision of the banks announced that it is considering mandating the creation of a mechanism that would allow the linkages to be included in the mortgages, but the final decision on the issue has not yet been made.
The price of fuel is rising - and Israelis will have to pay more than NIS 8 per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline will be NIS 8.08 •
At the same time, the reduction of half a NIS per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022
A record of a decade: the price of gasoline will jump by 36 shekels per liter - and will be more than NIS 8 per liter as of July 1.
The new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08 and those who wish to enjoy full service will be required to pay another 21 cents per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel fuel tax will be extended until the end of 2022 - the Tax Authority said.
As mentioned, the price increase is due to the continued increase in oil prices, against the background of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the increase in the dollar exchange rate.
If it weren't for the half-shekel discount that the government has been subsidizing since April, the price of fuel would have exceeded the all-time high - 8.25 shekels per liter.
The discount expires at the end of July and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting the publication for public comments of a decree extending the tax reduction on gasoline, which is half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting on August 10, another reduction of half a shekel will be established, so that only from this date the price of a liter of gasoline will be reduced by one shekel until November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
"We have reached a situation where I don't remember five months in a row of excess in state revenues.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We have been working for a week on the extension of the excise, gasoline and diesel tax by four months - instead of half a shekel per shekel.
It is good for the industry and the citizen.
If we lower, it will affect inflation, lower production and lower the cost of living.
As Minister of Finance, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus on this first," said Minister Lieberman at the Israel Democracy Institute's Horvitz Conference on Economy and Society.
As of today, more than half of the price of fuel is the taxes collected by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high rate of taxation compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic effect on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household expenses and business expenses, the prices of public transportation and flights, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most business-friendly city
Petah Tikva came in second place in the ranking of doing business by the Ministry of Economy •
After them: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon Lezion •
Minister Barbiei: "The corona has emphasized the importance of local government in business development"
.
Ashdod is the friendliest city for small and medium businesses.
This is the third year in a row - this is what the index of doing business in the local authorities found of the Agency for Small and Medium Businesses in the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranked the local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
After them are placed in order: Ashkelon, Rishon Lezion, Tel Aviv-Yafo, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beer Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the index of local authorities.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a working tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance with other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters that are tested in each authority, which examine the level of "friendliness" of the authority to the businesses in its area.
The index divides the authorities into three size groups according to the number of inhabitants, since a local authority of up to 50 thousand inhabitants is not similar to a local authority of more than 150 thousand inhabitants.
Tel Aviv jumped this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and property taxes.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to 12th place and Netanya dropped from fifth place to 13th place.
A drop in rating does not mean that the authority's service to businesses has deteriorated, and in many cases it results from the fact that the service of other authorities to businesses has improved more and they have gone up in rating, while the authority that has dropped in rating has improved its services to businesses less.
Among the newcomers in the ranking can be found Petah Tikva, which rose from sixth place to second place, and Rehovot, which rose from 12th place to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
"Business - engine of growth"
The ranking shows that Nof HaGilil is a leader in local authorities that include between 50 and 150 thousand residents.
After it are located Kiryat Motzkin, Meta Binyamin, Modi'in-Maccabim-Reot, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
In the 28th and last place is Tiberias.
"The index is intended to encourage local authorities to make it easier for small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the time the business opens and throughout its activity with the authorities," says the Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbibai.
"The businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of the business output and about 60% of the employed in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct influence on the businesses located there.
The corona virus emphasized the importance of local government and we saw that authorities that acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, became the first governmental interface for them."
Ran Kuiti, director of the Small and Medium Business Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities play a central and essential part in the ability of businesses in their field to thrive and flourish.
In the last two years, when we are dealing with the corona crisis, the authorities have a greater weight in helping businesses survive in their field and survive in general."
2021 by mail: 20 packages per household - and a jump in their weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a jump of 36% compared to 2020 •
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight was 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average per household - this is according to Israel Post data obtained by Israel Hayom.
The amount of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, when 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019 - when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there was a jump of more than 36% per year in the weight of packages arriving from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products from abroad arrived in Israel, a jump of 36% compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package jumped by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The jump in package weight is mainly influenced by two major trends, both from the seller's and the buyer's side: the major shopping sites abroad combine items into one shipment and no longer send each product from the "shopping basket" in separate packaging.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the fast delivery of the shipments, within a few days from the moment of the order, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which those buyers wish to receive close to making the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month in which the most packages arrived from abroad with the highest weight and the highest number of items is the month of December, with 4.2 million packages with a total weight of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
Black Friday effect
More packages arrived in December than any other month, apparently following the November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
The large orders start arriving in Israel between one and two weeks after the purchase.
Research: Most employees in the economy are not aware that they can receive tax refunds
Many employees receive money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels •
Have you changed jobs?
Did you go out to Halat?
Did you move from the city to the settlement?
You may be entitled to receive a significant amount in a simple procedure •
All the details are inside
Most employees are not aware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can add up to high amounts.
The State Comptroller stated in a report from about two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds in the amount of 3.6 billion shekels, which means that you should also check whether you are entitled to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a high amount, since four out of five employees are entitled to tax refunds.
In practice, on the other hand, they serve several tens of thousands of employees per year.
If you think that these funds have gone down the drain anyway, think again: employees can apply to the IRS for refunds for six years back.
The Tax:On company conducted an in-depth study among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax refunds during the year 2020.
The company has over 30 thousand customers, so the sample reflects their dispersion in terms of groups in the population and in terms of gender, ages and geography.
The data shows that during the year 2020, due to the outbreak of the Corona crisis and the spending of hundreds of thousands of workers on unemployment benefits, there were a number of significant changes, the center of which was a 15% increase in the amount of the average reimbursement to a single family, which amounted to NIS 4,300 per year.
The reason is that the tax dues are lower than the salaries, so there is a gap between what the employee paid as tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received in 2020 by a client of the company was NIS 121,054 for refunds over the past 6 years.
What can you get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons to receive tax refunds is a change in the workplace.
81% of the people who changed jobs during the year received a tax refund in the average amount of NIS 2,943.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data shows that 74% of the women who gave birth and were on maternity leave for more than 16 weeks were entitled to a refund in the average amount of NIS 3,538 for that year
Another reason for reimbursement is donations.
100% of people donating and paying taxes got a refund.
Another factor for reimbursement is not registering credit points for alimony. 63%
For the divorced, we did not update a credit point for alimony, therefore the tax refund for each year that such a credit point was not updated is NIS 2,616.
Due to unemployment - spending on unemployment benefits: 93% of those who were sick or unemployed and who earned over NIS 12,000 received a tax refund of NIS 4021 for that year.
Other reasons for tax refunds are: refund for life insurance payments, life insurance on a mortgage, refund for a qualifying return, refund for losses in securities, failure to register credit points for a man for giving birth and distribution of tax refunds according to geographic location.
- 94% of the people who deposited for personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were entitled to a tax refund.
In an inspection conducted on every million shekels of a 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax refund for the period is over 20,000 shekels for the entire mortgage period
100% of those who move to a qualifying settlement received a tax refund for the year of the move since confirmation of residency in a qualifying settlement is given only after 12 months from the day the resident became a qualifying resident, thus effectively the first year full tax is paid.
79% of the customers holding securities were entitled to a tax refund for the aforementioned years.
However, it is important for those who hold securities to check every year since losses are not rolled over from year to year but only through the submission of a report.
56% of the men who had a child do not register credit points in the year of birth on the payslip.
The repayment rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
CEO of tax:on, Tal Carmon: "The corona crisis has meant that the salaried public in Israel has become much more active.
He is interested, checks and demands what he deserves in returns from the income tax.
It turns out that hundreds of thousands of Israelis sitting at home, on unemployment benefits or after layoffs, for many months, caused many employees to take a deep look at what they deserve from the state.
It is important to know that today all procedures for receiving tax refunds can be carried out digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past.'
The job market: fewer job applicants, more pay
AllJobs 2021 summary report: at the top of the demand - jobs without experience •
The scope of jobs offered increased by 50% •
"Looking for a job, but not storming the market"
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decrease in the number of resumes sent, and for each position only 23 candidates competed on average, compared to 41 candidates the previous year - according to a report by the AllJobs website summarizing the year 2021, on the corona crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel
According to the report, the job seekers were mainly interested in areas saturated with jobs such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 CVs were sent.
However, the jobs without experience led the demand with more than 38 thousand searches - probably due to the return of young people without professional experience to look for immediate work, at the end of the Halat payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and maintenance had just under 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the corona crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was NIS 11,675 gross.
The monthly salary in the software field was NIS 17,915 on average, and in information systems analysis it was NIS 17,140.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a wage gap of more than NIS 2,000: in the center of the country it was NIS 12,500 on average, compared to NIS 10,795 in the north and NIS 10,135 in the south.
From a gender perspective, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the number of hours, remained at 36%.
Men earned NIS 13,295, compared to women's wages of NIS 9,740.
Trying to get back into the groove
On the business side, horizontal growth was recorded in almost all branches of the economy, and businesses craved working hands.
Thus, the offer of jobs increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40 thousand jobs in AllJobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them testified that they intend to increase the total number of hires, but 72% understand that they will have difficulty doing so this year.
The largest offer was for jobs without experience - and there were more than 58 thousand of them on the site.
They were followed by customer service and administration positions with approximately 44,000 jobs in each field, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 vacancies, and warehouse workers still in demand with 19,000 vacancies.
Einav Boimfeld, director of research and content at AllJobs: "The job seekers are trying to get back into the groove but are not attacking the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged disconnection from the work circle makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to make a living."
