The report also states that the minutes of the meetings are published with a significant delay, if at all •
Also, the auditor recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activity - and updating the procedures for the work of the basket •
Another deficiency that was found relates to the fact that since the committee began its activities, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the scope of uses and utilization of the drugs in the basket - which would have allowed for the analysis and control of the budget given to them.
The Medicines Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees on our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new medicines that will be given to the public free of charge through the health insurance funds - but a new report by the State Comptroller published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without any control reports being made on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervise and review its activities.
"Israel Hayom" correspondent Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing revelations in "Israel Hayom" about the failures of the medicine basket.
According to Matanyahu Engelman's report, he recommends "to carry out corrections and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will lead to a better utilization of the health services basket budget that the public is entitled to".
Throughout the years of the existence of the mechanism of the addition to the basket of medicines, in the years 1998-2021, medicines totaling eight billion shekels were added to the state budget - with the addition varying annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add approximately 800 new medicines and technologies to the basket of health services, with a total annual cost of more than two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated to expand the basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
In most of the years of the commission's operation (90% of the time), the amount of the budget supplement was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor points out that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual supplement in order to enable certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in the basket work is lacking".
Thus, for example, the working procedure of the basket committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 109-160 days, when sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; because of this, the ability of the bidders - patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies - to submit repeated applications as soon as possible and relevant, after they have learned from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and corrected their proposals and carried out A renewed assessment regarding the possibility of accepting them in the next round," the auditor noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules established in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions - only one financial comment was submitted
Another criticism of Engelman concerns the preliminary procedure of the evaluation of the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that about half (46%) of the submitted technologies did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for rejection.
Another shortcoming concerns the activity of the sub-committee of the drug basket, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The auditor recommends adding a public representative or exploring the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
In the procedure according to which the health services basket committee operates, it is established that "an economic evaluation must be submitted" for a request to add a medicine to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic evaluation was submitted out of thousands of submissions - and the committee makes its decisions without an economic evaluation.
For example, for the discussions of the basket committee for the years 2019-2021, requests were submitted to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
From the report it emerged that the requests were not accompanied by economic assessments, including an assessment of the amount that could be saved due to reducing the damage caused by obesity-related diseases or due to the ability to avoid gastric bypass surgery.
It also appears that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are not in line with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparation for the treatment of the increase in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The auditor also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the health insurance funds, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccinations, provided by the Ministry of Health ("the third supplement") have also been included in the medicine basket.
This, when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retrospectively.
In the last six years, NIS 74 million from the addition to the medicine basket was used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the procedures for the work of the basket and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is necessary for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as "drugs without additional cost", the use of which does not cost the health insurance funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor suggests examining the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and shortened route, so that the basket of drugs can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision of the use of particularly expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the basket committee's work began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health did not ask the health funds to report and did not monitor the scope of uses and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and control the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published that refer to the years 2006-2009, and these were also published considerably late (the last one was published this year and dealt with the utilization of the budget in 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting the data and analyzing it, to the irrelevance of the conclusions emerging from the test after such a long period of time, to suboptimal pricing by the subcommittee and to making decisions based on inconclusive findings," the report states.
Also, the ministry does not audit and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not learned lessons.
These are 10 medicines that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2016-2021).
On this, the auditor wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health carry out individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the scope of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the sub-committee, and about how the estimates are prepared when pricing the drugs and technologies and improve them."
"Horrifying and unimaginable": a stormy discussion in the health committee about the poisoning in Beit Dafna
The parameters of the first Jose who passed away were normal ten minutes before her death •
Chairman of the committee, MK Silman: "If the people there cared about the kitchen being like at home - it wouldn't look like this."
Ten minutes before the first 40-year-old Jose from the "Beit Dafna" daycare center in Holon died of food poisoning, her medical parameters were taken which were normal, the director of the daycare center claimed today (Tuesday) at the hearing of the health committee.
