A model for healing: three senior doctors tell about their mentors
Prof. Galia Rahav misses the wit and wisdom of the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, especially during the days of the plague •
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh does not forget, even from the height of his position, the push from the late Prof. Shaul Soknik •
And Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev thanks Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld for the lesson in identifying with the patients •
Three key people in the hospitals write about those who inspired them and encouraged them to be better, both as caregivers and as people.
Three senior doctors, three teachers of life and the profession: on the occasion of Israeli Doctor's Day, "Israel Hayom" invited Prof. Galia Rahav, Dr. Shlomi Kodesh and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev to remember the figures who accompanied them at the beginning - and helped them become who they are today .
Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba
About the late Prof. Marvin Shapira
The meeting that opened my eyes - and changed my life
If I hadn't met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the infectious diseases unit at Hadassah Hospital, I would probably have remained a specialist in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to pursue it.
I met him in the corridors of Hadassah, sometime in the 80s of the last century.
For a moment I didn't think I would leave internal medicine, as I liked the patient care itself; But Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also reflected in neurology, also in internal medicine, and basically in every field.
I thank him for bringing me to this field.
Throughout, I liked his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor with every fiber of his soul, who loved the patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to examine everything in depth.
He was a real and honest person, without ego, qualities that I really liked about him.
Initially, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and influenced me the most, I intended to choose my father, the late Dr. Yosef Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go into medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapira.
Both of them, for example, coined proverbs that doctors use to this day - for example "tissue is de personio", that is, taking a biopsy of tissue from the infected organ makes it possible to know which drugs should be given; or "Once You Use It, You Lose It", which is intended to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to bacteria becoming resistant to it.
The late Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked in Hadassah and father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family at Sheva I cried.
He was something - a witty and clever epidemiologist, who volunteered for anything.
He never complained, not even during his severe illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat epidemics, and he is sorely missed at this time.
If he were with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted him, and I'm sure he was one of the leaders of the team for dealing with epidemics.
Brought to light: Mittal Yassur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, director of Soroka Hospital
About the late Prof. Shaul Soknik
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors
.
I met the late Prof. Shaul Suknik for the first time when I was a student in the fourth year of medical studies, and I did a rotation in internal medicine in the 4th internal medicine department that he managed.
Later I returned to the department also in the sixth year rotation, and I did the final thesis of the medical school under his guidance, writing a computer simulation about a patient with polyarthritis (inflammation of multiple joints).
Shaul influenced every significant juncture in my professional life over 20 years, and was the most significant person in shaping my character as a doctor; Not only professionally, but also - and above all - from a personal and human point of view.
During the internship I was debating between family medicine and internal medicine, and I consulted him about the choice of specialization.
In the end I chose to specialize in internal medicine with him in Soroka.
During the internship, he provided me with constant guidance, in a variety of ways - in scientific writing (sorry Saul, I was not persistent enough), in communication with patients, working in a multi-professional team - an area in which the department excelled - and basically, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I recognize in myself, as a doctor and as a manager, characteristics that come from a question.
When I finished my internship and was debating whether to go for a training period abroad, Shaul pushed and guided me, and helped me with letters of recommendation and advice on how to conduct myself.
The training period was a very important period for my professional development, and without Shaul's support and encouragement I am not sure that this would have happened.
On my return, when I received an offer to join the hospital's management, Shaul was once again the one who supported and helped.
Later we managed complex periods together in the internal medicine division.
Shaul knew how to combine in a wonderful way the teacher, the manager, the friend and the partner of the team, without his different roles interfering with each other.
I aspire to be as successful as him in this special combination.
He raised generations of students, interns and interns, who are today throughout the medical system in Israel, and perpetuate his memory and his work with their excellent work.
I am honored to be among this group.
Brought to light: Ilya Yegorov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, director of the Schneider Pediatrics Center
About Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and especially listening.
Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld, founder and former director of the Intensive Care Unit at the Schneider Pediatric Center, taught me to be an intensive care physician, but more than that - he taught me to think.
The obvious thing I learned from him is to take care of the most complex, sickest children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just a moment ago, and are now between life and death.
The obvious thing is to have very difficult conversations, perhaps the most difficult, with families who did not imagine that they would find themselves in these complex situations in the intensive care unit with their children.
Sounds strange, but it goes without saying.
But I learned significant and even deeper things from him.
Looking back, since I am a doctor who is a manager and a manager who is a doctor, the connection between the worlds is clear to me today; The education I received from Dr. Scheinfeld connects them.
Dr. Scheinfeld taught me to listen attentively to many things: to listen to the children, to listen to the monitor, to listen to the nursing nurses, to the nursing teams both young and old, and to listen to the parents.
All this should be done not only to communicate more correctly and more successfully, but to constantly collect a lot of information that can prevent the next deterioration.
The preventive processes in child care exist everywhere, and of course also in intensive care.
Listening and conversation stimulate a deeper understanding, both on the part of the treating staff and on the part of the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true when looking at a complete system.
The more in-depth and more rigorous understanding that takes place, integrating all the treating factors in the discourse, the more accurate the decision-making process will be, adapted to the situation, and above all - early enough in order to prevent future, immediate or distant damages.
This is why Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld is much more than an inspirational figure for me.
He is a person who taught me a lot of medicine, but mostly taught me to think quickly and accurately, listen - and then apply.
