Medical negligence in the various stages of childbirth
In order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence
A birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family's life.
However, unfortunately, births sometimes end in serious damage caused to the mother or newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury to the newborn or the mother, there is room to examine the chain of events that led to the injury and even consider applying for legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical negligence will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical staff during the various stages of birth that caused the damage and, as he deems appropriate, will consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It must be emphasized that not every error in treatment by the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that the management was negligent.
When then is it negligence?
When the doctor's mistake resulted from a lack of skill or a deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused damage to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not acted in this way.
In this article we will examine the different stages of childbirth, we will explain the complications that may occur in each of the stages and when they amount to medical negligence.
Stage the contractions
The labor phase lasts on average between 8 and 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix is gradually opened (to allow the passage of the fetus during birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most of the cases of medical negligence during the labor stage deal with the failure to recognize fetal distress before birth, which caused damage to the newborn, sometimes even manifesting itself in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by failure to recognize or delay in recognizing perinatal asphyxia, which is manifested in the failure of oxygen supply to the brain tissue of the fetus.
In general, monitoring the condition of the mother and correct interpretation of the monitor that follows the activity of the fetal heart should lead to early detection of the development of fetal distress, allowing the medical team to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases where the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen or the team does not correctly interpret the data in front of it and in particular the fetal monitor or reacts late to the distress expressed on the monitor - may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by prolapse of the umbilical cord, as well as by a uterine rupture that was not detected in time.
Even in these difficult events, it is appropriate to find out whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, attorney Anna Raif Liganza, from the office of Caspi Seror & Co., which specializes in representing victims of medical negligence, says that her office handled the claim of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the fetus's head was too high, thus causing the umbilical cord to prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and damage to the oxygen supply to the fetal brain (as a result of the pressure of the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and to be born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, a lawyer said that her office filed a lawsuit due to the serious medical negligence of the staff of the maternity department at a large hospital who, during the birth, did not recognize clear signs at the time that required a real suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the area of the surgical scar from her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that was ejected through the tear in his mother's womb into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until he was rescued at a late stage when he was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the asphyxiation and the damage caused to the newborn, meaning that the damage was caused by said negligence and not by any other reason or factor.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out through the examination of medical indicators which, according to the medical literature, only in their existence is there a causal relationship between the asphyxiation and the brain injury.
Among other things, the indicators of the level of acidity in the blood of the fetus, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic damage and more are examined.
the death of the fetus
The active labor stage
The active labor stage begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical phase.
Delay in childbirth and avoidance of caesarean section
In some cases, a dysfunctional birth develops, that is, a lack of progress in the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a caesarean section, in order to prevent various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in delivery.
"There are cases in which failure to perform a caesarean section on time may cause irreversible damage to the fetus," attorney Raif-Liganza explained to us.
"For example, we managed a medical malpractice claim for the death of a newborn child caused by a significant delay in performing a caesarean section.
Contrary to any known medical practice, the medical staff did not know how to recognize the fetal distress and perform a caesarean section despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused a lot of systemic damage to the woman, which finally led to her death shortly after her birth."
Malpractice in vacuum delivery
In situations where the mother or the fetus is in significant danger that requires an extremely quick termination of the birth, a vacuum birth (empty vagina) is sometimes performed.
In this process, using a vacuum, a "cap" is attached to the embryo's head and the embryo is pulled out by force.
Naturally, this operation involves dangers and may cause damage to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great care, precision and skill.
In these cases, medical negligence may manifest itself in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the mandatory instructions and performs the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for a longer time than allowed or when, despite the failure of many attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the operation more of the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases, if the negligent operation of the vacuum caused damage to the newborn - among other things, it could cause cranial damage and bleeding that could cause the development of brain damage - there is room for filing a tort claim.
Paralysis in the name of ERB
Paralysis named after Erv, here is a congenital nerve injury in the brachial plexus (nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is appropriate to check whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetrician.
The injury manifests itself in the weakness of the hand muscles and can reach complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of 'dislocated shoulders' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the shoulders of the fetus are trapped inside the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the evaluation of the weight of the fetus indicated that it is a macrosomic fetus, meaning that it is expected to be born weighing more than 4.5 kilograms and according to the guidelines it is better to give birth to the mother by caesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kilograms, a caesarean section should be considered in light of the risk factors, including gestational diabetes and the prolongation of the second stage of labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores the abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to continue with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder dislocation and paralysis due to ERB materializes, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in AA 2694/90, the Supreme Court stated that "the risk that shoulder stenosis will occur during childbirth can be predicted in advance with one or another degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is a fear of its occurrence, is to perform a caesarean section."
Placental exit stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the exit of the newborn and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process lasts in most cases up to half an hour from the moment the baby is born and often occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical team.
After the placenta comes out, the medical team will check whether it came out in its entirety or whether there are parts of the placenta left in the uterus.
During this stage, complications may occur that may cause serious harm to the mother.
One of the well-known complications resulting from placental remnants remaining in the uterus is called "Asherman's syndrome", the scarring of the uterine wall is the result of inflammation caused by placental remnants remaining in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the endometrium in a way that does not allow the pregnancy to root.
Therefore, in cases where the medical staff did not recognize that there were placenta remnants or did not take all measures to prevent damage to the endometrium despite the suspicion of placenta remnants in the uterus, it is possible that this is medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
The death of the mother
Maternal death during childbirth is quite rare.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy of life to the whole family turns, unfortunately, into the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the woman giving birth on time or reacts late to said bleeding.
"For example...", Attorney Reif-Liganza told us, "our office filed a claim concerning the death of a woman giving birth, when in that case the medical team ignored and did not respond to the worrisome vital signs of the woman giving birth, for many hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a complication It is known of the underlying disease from which she suffered."
"In another case...", said Attorney Reif-Liganza, "our office represented the relatives of a mother who died after giving birth to twins due to bleeding that originated from the caesarean section that was not properly sutured.
In that case, the woman in labor complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and clinical condition, reacting late only after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death."
uterine loss
In serious cases, medical negligence during childbirth can lead to a hysterectomy, says attorney Raif Lingza: "Our office filed a lawsuit against a hospital based on a hysterectomy due to medical negligence after the birth.
In that case, the woman giving birth, a 31-year-old woman, lost her uterus due to a lack of proper treatment for massive bleeding observed by the medical team after the birth, and despite this, the actions that could have prevented the damage were not taken in time."
What are the compensations awarded in lawsuits for medical negligence in childbirth?
Newborn compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being given for pain and suffering, nursing care and paid treatment, wage losses and pension for the victim and even his parents and additional damage components.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for wage and pension losses is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation accessories, the cost of adapting housing to the baby's needs, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case on a case-by-case basis and according to its circumstances," says Attorney Reif-Liganza, and she adds and notes that "today, most lawsuits on the grounds of medical negligence end in a compromise that weighs the chances and risks that each party has in managing the procedure," but the attorney added and said that "There are cases where the procedure ends only with a verdict, so if the lawsuit is not dismissed, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages and for example, in a lawsuit conducted by our office, the district court awarded a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress compensation in excess of ten million shekels" .
In conclusion
Medical malpractice in childbirth is undoubtedly the nightmare of every family.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic result, by an attorney skilled in managing medical malpractice claims, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of the eye disease keratoconus in the south
A study revealed that there is a connection between the development of the disease and close marriages •
The highest incidence was found in the Bedouin sector •
Expert: "It is possible that in any sector with many weddings between cousins, we will find a high incidence of the disease."
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some visual impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and find the right solutions to prevent the situation from worsening.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted that help to understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide a research basis for the suspicion that the eye disease keratoconus is a genetic disease.
A recent study, which dealt with changing the shape of the cornea from a dome to a cone, discovered that the cause of the disease and the weakness of the cornea and the distortion of its shape is related to an enzymatic imbalance, as a result of which the free radicals may damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of that lack of enzymes is genetic, a fact that strengthens the hypothesis that keratoconus is a hereditary disease.
According to Prof. Ariela Gordon-Shag, head of the department of optometric sciences at Hadassah Academic College, "in a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, a prevalence of keratoconus of 3.2% was found.
The highest incidence was in students from the Bedouin sector - 20% had keratoconus, but it was a relatively small sample."
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "There is a high prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that consanguineous marriages are a risk factor for keratoconus.
Thus in any sector with many weddings between cousins, we may find a high incidence."
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where there is a family history of keratoconus disease, all family members must undergo an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Erza Fruchter, a B.Sc clinical optometrist, "there are ten times more visits to the clinic from distant peripheral areas, mainly from the south, compared to the center."
Fruchter adds that "In the last decade, I noticed that most of the patients apply from the outskirts, especially from the Beer Sheva area.
This is mainly due to a high incidence of marriages within the family (mainly in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of how to properly treat the problem."
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus usually develops during adolescence or in the late teens (ages 15-16 or 20).
The disease includes a decrease in vision, at the same time as an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients show distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These signs worsen with the development of the disease, which usually develops slowly and gradually over years.
However, the disease may also develop at a rapid pace and reach its peak in just a few months.
Many of the patients even testify to increased sensitivity to light.
