A senior police officer: "Government policy and setting goals are required here"
The Israel Police has indeed launched an operation to eradicate the phenomenon of illegal residents, but the road is still long •
Today in the State of Israel there is no single factor that encompasses this whole issue."
"If you want to deal with the phenomenon of illegal residents, a government policy is required, from which goals, tasks and responsibilities must be derived.
Today, in the State of Israel, there is no single agency that covers this whole issue," a senior police officer told Israel Hayom.
Until a month and a half ago, before the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon manifested itself in about 20 to 30 thousand Sheba'im who enter every day through the loopholes in the fence.
On top of that, between 100 and 110 thousand Palestinians with work permits enter to work in Israel every day through 34 controlled crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six Day War, and the number of permits in each branch is limited by the quota set by the political rank according to the security, economic and political situation in the State of Israel.
The permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, Sheba is not necessarily a Palestinian whose entry is prohibited due to criminal involvement or connection to terrorist attacks, but in many cases it is Palestinians whose entry is prohibited because they do not meet the permitted permit quota.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff and Elad were indeed considered Shabahim, but were not monitored, because they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required the security forces to monitor their movements.
"Therefore, their entry through the loopholes in the fence is meaningless," says a senior security official, "those who want to carry out an attack can also enter the country through the controlled crossings, and there have already been such cases in the past.
Thousands of arrests
Following the attack in Elad and in light of numerous warnings of attacks, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal residents.
By the end of the week, about 16,000 Shebaim were arrested.
Of these, about 600 were investigated and criminal cases were opened, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to the police prosecution policy, proceedings against illegal residents are carried out only against habitual criminals or people who repeat the act over and over again (recidivists).
An illegal resident who is arrested for the first time is interrogated, documented and returned to the territories.
Sometimes this is repeated a second time as well, but only the third time he is arrested, imprisoned and charged with illegal stay.
According to the law, if an illegal resident is caught within a range of about 50 to 100 meters from each side of the separation fence, his treatment is carried out by the military prosecution.
Data received by Israel Hayom shows that in 2021, the police handled 40,010 illegal residents, drivers and squatters.
7,405 illegal residents were arrested and a criminal case was opened against 19,533.
The number of employers, transporters and shippers handled by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and criminal cases were opened against 5,640.
"The foundations of the Shabaim phenomenon do not depend on the police, not on the IDF, not on Israeli society, not on Palestinian society.
They depend on other factors," says a senior member of the law enforcement system.
"In order to address this phenomenon, their motivation to go to work in Israel must be sterilized, and on the Israeli side, a price must be charged to prevent them from crossing the fence.
Sources involved in the issue claim that the failure to collect the price is due, among other things, to a lack of prison places and the fact that arrests are only made when there are related offenses or it is a recidivist.
Legal sources claim that the decision to collect a price from Shabah only starting with his third arrest was made, among other things, because the courts cannot cope with the number of arrests carried out every day.
Whoever examines the punishment as well, will find that it is not a deterrent."
There is great complexity
Sheba," says a police official, "is a complex person."
He can be a father of a family who entered Israel to work to earn a few shekels and return.
This is the basic platform, and it is used by many types of Shebaim who enter the country to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks."
Sheba can be an adult or a minor.
In the past, 16-year-old illegal residents were caught by the police and even 8- and 10-year-old children were sent by their parents to road junctions, to earn a few shekels a day from drivers.
"It also makes the matter complex, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and file an indictment against them for neglect," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel in manual labor.
The most unusual are electrical works or advanced construction works.
In the past, there were also local authorities that employed Shebaim in garbage removal, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 passes, there are about 18 major passes.
There are passages for vehicles and goods, there are passages through which only people pass, and there are passages which are both.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the crossings authority.
The Sheba'im are usually driven into the country by private drivers, as it is easy money.
"There are those who do this for a living, and there are gangs whose main business is transporting Shebaim," says a senior police official, "usually most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.
It can reach NIS 100 to NIS 300 per person.
Registered companies do not engage in this, because if the company is caught, it must be closed."
The police emphasize that under certain conditions, driving a Sheba can be considered a crime.
"A taxi driver who works with licenses in accordance with licensing and insurance, who picks up Palestinians at regular points and at regular times, including a regular order, is not breaking the law," says a senior police officer, "whoever knows he is a Sheva driver, usually picks them up in the dead of night at hiding spots, including dropping them off in hidden spots.
For the most part, these guys drive with a car from Chokmak because they know that their car will be stolen, so they prefer to drive in an old car."
