Research states: Zoom meetings harm creativity
About 2,100 engineers and academics in the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem - some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings •
The result: a virtual meeting hurts creativity and thinking outside the box •
The leader of the research at Columbia University: "The visual focus on the screen harms the process of generating ideas" •
Nechama Forta: There is no harm to work productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the effect of meetings through video software on the creativity of the participants in them, compared to meetings held face to face.
Unfortunately, it has been found that creativity does suffer in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, assistant professor from Columbia University - was whether remote meetings using a computer preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The research itself began already in 2016 but received a big boost in the two years of the Corona, during which many employees moved to work from home.
"People in an in-person meeting move around the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking," says Brooks.
"In a computer meeting, on the other hand, the concentration on maintaining eye contact with the others comes at the expense of the creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which hurts the broad and expansive idea generation process."
The space is shrinking.
In order to examine the results of the experiment and ascertain whether they would repeat themselves, they were tested twice - once at Columbia University and once again in real life - on engineers who knew each other from a prior acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty members and students into two parts - in one, the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and in the second, they were asked to do this via a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide themselves in a similar way and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who works on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help them create ideas, whereas in a video meeting, thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
"When the people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations in them.
On the other hand, the research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this way reduces innovation and the creation of ideas through looking at the environment and thinking outside.
There is no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush the employees back to the offices, the researchers point out that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor the people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the damage is focused only on creativity and not on the other forms of working in front of a computer."
Prof. Ellen Langer, professor of psychology at Harvard University, also qualifies the findings.
According to her, "There is a difference between mere creativity, such as new uses for frisbees (one of the research questions; AG) and work solutions.
It is also possible that when the employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or that they work from home, creativity will improve."
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also suggested future research in which such meetings would be interrupted for thinking and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
