Exemption from isolation for the vaccinated and those recovering from non-red countries, the foreign tourists are returning.
Landers in Israel received notices from the Ministry of Health that they are exempt from the obligation to isolate upon receiving a negative answer to the corona test •
Only after that did the ministry issue an official announcement stating that only travelers from orange countries were involved, although returnees from red countries also reported receiving the announcement •
In addition: tourists from orange destinations will be able to enter Israel, and it is expected that many red destinations will be removed from the list.
At the peak of an epidemic - the end of isolation for those returning from abroad?
The Ministry of Health sent notices this morning (Monday) to returnees to Israel, according to which they are exempt from isolation upon receiving a negative answer to the corona test they performed after landing in Israel.
These are also returnees from red countries.
Some of the messages sent informed the returnees that they could be released after receiving a negative answer or after 24 hours at the latest, and some of them received the exemption after receiving the negative answer.
Only then did an official announcement come out from the Ministry of Health stating that starting tonight at midnight, January 4, 2022, whether vaccinated or recovering, the returnees from orange countries will undergo a PCR test in Israel and enter isolation for 24 hours or until receiving a negative result (whichever comes first).
The decision will be enshrined in the decree of the Director General of the Ministry of Health and will be submitted for approval to the Health Committee of the Knesset.
The ministry clarified that vaccinated or convalescents who have already returned to Israel from an orange state and received a negative result from the PCR test they performed upon entering Israel, will end the isolation tonight at midnight and are not obligated to perform a second test.
However, travelers from red states reported that they also received the message.
Those who have not been vaccinated or recovered and returned from an orange country, will enter home isolation for 14 days, with the possibility of shortening isolation upon receiving a negative result in a PCR test performed starting on the 7th day after landing in Israel (the day of landing is the first day).
The decision to remove most of the restrictions on flights and especially on those who are vaccinated comes a day before the High Court hearing submitted by the Association of Travel Ministries, the Headquarters for Open Skies and the Hotel Association.
At the hearing that will take place tomorrow, the petitioners are expected to demand that all other red states be removed from the list, while the one who backs them up in his opinion is Professor Itamar Grotto.
Foreigners will also be able to enter.
The Prime Minister and the Ministers of Foreign Affairs, Health, the Interior, Tourism and Transportation agreed that starting Sunday, January 9, 2022, the entry of vaccinated/recovered foreigners (as defined by the Ministry of Health) from orange countries will be allowed - subject to filling out an online form ahead of time, performing a PCR or antigen test before immigration to the plane, performing a PCR test upon entering Israel followed by entering isolation for 24 hours or receiving a negative test result (whichever comes first).
Foreigners who are not vaccinated/not recovering (as defined by the Ministry of Health) will not be allowed to enter Israel.
Foreigners from red countries, with the exception of those whose entry has been approved by the Exceptions Committee, will not be allowed to enter Israel.
The group schedule will not be renewed at this stage.
And what about red states?
The committee for the classification of countries in the Ministry of Health recommends to the government that the following countries be removed from the list of red countries and transferred to the orange list: South Africa, Hungary, Nigeria, Spain, Portugal, France, Canada.
The countries that remain at this point in the list of red countries: the United Arab Emirates, the United States, Ethiopia, the United Kingdom, Tanzania, Mexico, Switzerland and Turkey.
Another option that the Ministry of Health is considering is to exempt from isolation the vaccinated returning from red countries.
